descriptions: Our group helped in planning for, and developed software tools for the repository described here
In the 'DAS-month' repository mentioned above, ETH contributed 4 distinct datasets to the project

The additional 7 publications mentioned below each include links to publicly accessible datasets and codes. They are available through different platforms (e.g., github, zenodo, ETH Library, our group website, etc.) as we experimented with different sharing methods and workflows
Our group software and models are available at https://cos.ethz.ch/software.html and https://cos.ethz.ch/models.html . These include some DAS related projects, but also other topics
Software to read, write and visualize DAS data is developed publicly here
Each of the 8 publications listed below include some amount of data and corresponding code for analyses, all shared openly. Many build on the unified software framework developed on github

Along with the software mentioned above, we outline practices for documentation and workflows for new projects. Along with the software on Github, Jupyter notebooks describe how data can be cleanly read, written and visualized

We joined an already planned workshop on sharing seismic data across governmental borders, the “EPOS/EMSC Seismology Workshop and GFZ International Training Course” in Podgorica, Montenegro. We were invited to help lead discussions on upcoming technologies and best practices. The section was titled: “On the varied uses of Distributed Acoustic Sensing (DAS), and future challenges in data management.”

Collaborative datasets from the DAS Month project connected us with 24 other universities and started ongoing discussion of data handling best practices.
Involvement with discussions and future infrastructure planning.
Connections with Istanbul Municipality and Bogazici Kandilli Observatory for urban seismic hazard characterization.
Collaboration with professor and students at Colorado School of Mines; the professor is now visiting for her sabbatical.
National Observatory of Athens and optics researchers at 3 different Greek Universities for further development of instrumentation.
Future project being planned for April of 2024.
Collaboration with Iceland Meteorological Office after sharing data during the Grindavik eruption, with plans for future analyses.
Connection to TotalEnergies which could bring significant projects and funding into the department.

The community DAS users and other fiber-optic sensing tools is rapidly expanding; the number of active academic researchers worldwide is easily at least 1000 people, and standardization of the ORD and FAIR practices will benefit all.

training_events.reasoning: The first entry describes a training/educational workshop event directly related to the project, with full details and high confidence. The second entry clarifies no further training events. Therefore, the correct value is one event with its description, and no URLs.

publications.reasoning: All provided publication descriptions and URLs were compiled from both extractions. Counts are additive as there is no duplication in titles or DOIs/URLs. All confidence scores are output as provided with no modification.

presentations.reasoning: Quantity and itemized descriptions for 19 presentations are directly and explicitly listed in the range page 8–10 (idx=1). The earlier summary (idx=0) listed zero, but the more thorough listing supersedes it. Only descriptions are present; there are no URLs in the extracted data. All confidences are drawn directly from the provided values (verbatim extraction).

industrial_collaborations.reasoning: The later document segment (idx: 1, pages 7-13) reports one new collaboration with TotalEnergies, with details given in the description and high confidence in the extraction. The earlier section (idx: 0, pages 0-7) has no such collaborations, but the later evidence overrides this. No URLs were present. Used verbatim extraction from the relevant segment.

config.system_prompt:
EXTRACTION STRATEGY:
  1. PRIMARY: Look for data in the specified location/table/section
  2. FALLBACK: If not found, search broader document context for semantically equivalent information
  3. FLEXIBILITY: Allow for format variations, OCR errors, and synonym usage

  LOCATION FLEXIBILITY:
  - Handle table format variations (column/row order, spacing, naming)
  - Consider synonyms and equivalent terms
  - Account for OCR/parsing errors that may affect document quality

  QUALITY STANDARDS:
  - Extract actual values found in the document
  - If uncertain, provide best interpretation with appropriate confidence
  - Only return null if the information category truly doesn't exist
  - Convert abbreviated amounts (k=1000) to full numbers where applicable
  

  REPORT OUTPUT FOCUS:
  - 15 standard output categories in "List of Outputs" table
  - Each category: quantity number, descriptions list, URLs list
  - Separate descriptions from URLs even when mixed in same cell
  - Academic collaborations vs Industrial partnerships (distinct categories)
  - Preserve all detailed descriptions and web addresses
